title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=\dim (V)]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[v\in  V]]></fr:tex> be a nonzero vector. We have the collection of vectors
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\{V, Tv, T^{2}v, …, T^{n}v\}]]></fr:tex>
Since this contains <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n+1]]></fr:tex> vectors, it must be <fr:link
type="local"
href="vectsp-000Q.xml"
addr="vectsp-000Q"
title="Linearly Independent Vectors">linearly dependent</fr:link>. Then there exists scalars <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},a_{1},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> not all zero, such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[0=a_{0}v+a_{1}Lv+a_{2}L^{2}v+…+a_{n}L^{n}v]]></fr:tex>
Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> be the largest index such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{m}\neq 0]]></fr:tex> (so all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{k}=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k>m]]></fr:tex> and we can just drop these terms). Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[v\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, we must have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m>0]]></fr:tex> (and even possibly <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m=n]]></fr:tex>). Consider the polynomial
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[p(z)=a_{0}+a_{1}z+…+a_{m}z^{m}.]]></fr:tex>
Then using the <fr:link
type="local"
href="complex-000N.xml"
addr="complex-000N"
title="">immediate consequences</fr:link> of the fundamental theorem of algebra, we can factorize <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)]]></fr:tex> as
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[p(z)=c(z-\lambda _{1})(…)(z-\lambda _{m})]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[c,\lambda _{1},…,\lambda _{m}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[c\neq 0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[0=a_{0}v+a_{1}Lv+a_{2}L^{2}v+…+a_{n}L^{n}v=p(L)v]]></fr:tex>
and
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[0=p(L)v=c(L-\lambda _{1}I)(…)(L-\lambda _{m}I)v]]></fr:tex>
which means at least one of the factors <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L-\lambda _{j}I]]></fr:tex> must be non-injective. This means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda _{j}]]></fr:tex> must be an eigenvalue of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
